  "prompt": "Can you travel at the speed of light?",
  "response": "No, according to our current understanding of physics, it is not possible for objects with mass to travel at the speed of light. The speed of light is approximately 299,792,458 meters per second (about 186,282 miles per second) in a vacuum. \n\nAs an object with mass approaches the speed of light, its energy and momentum increase without bound, requiring an infinite amount of energy to actually reach the speed of light. This is a consequence of Einstein's theory of relativity. Therefore, while particles without mass, such as photons, can travel at the speed of light, objects with mass, like humans and spacecraft, cannot.",
